==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈbɹeɪd/|lang=en}}
* {{homophones|lang=en|abrade}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|abraiden|lang=enm}}, {{term|abreiden||to start up, awake, move, reproach|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|ābreġdan||to move quickly, vibrate, draw, draw from, remove, unsheath, wrench, pull out, withdraw, take away, draw back, free from, draw up, raise, lift up, start up}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*uz-||out}} + {{m|gem-pro|*bregdaną||to move, swing}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bhrēḱ-}}, {{m|ine-pro|*bhrēǵ-||to shine}}, equivalent to {{prefix|a|braid|lang=en}}. Related to Dutch {{term|breien||to knit|lang=nl}}, German {{term|bretten||to knit|lang=de}}.

====Alternative forms====
* [[abray]]

====Verb====
{{en-verb|abraids|abraiding|abraided|past2=abraid}}

# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[wrench]] (something) out. {{defdate|10th-13th c.}}
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[wake up]]. {{defdate|11th-18th c.}}
#* '''1596''', {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, ''The Faerie Queene'', IV.6:
#*: But when as I did out of sleepe '''abray''', / I found her not where I her left whyleare […].
#* '''1600''', {{w|Edward Fairfax}}, The ''Jerusalem Delivered'' of Tasso, XIII, l:
#*: ''But from his study he at last '''abray'd''',''
#*:: ''Call'd by the hermit old...''
# {{context|intransitive|archaic|lang=en}} To [[spring]], [[start]], make a sudden movement. {{defdate|from 11th c.}}
# {{context|intransitive|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[shout]] out. {{defdate|15th-16th c.}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To rise in the stomach with nausea. {{defdate|16th-19th c.}}

